{{Youmay|the fictional game|[[Ringers (short story)|the short story]]}}
'''Ringers''' was a precision sport in which individual players, called [[tosser]]s, competed to throw [[metal]]lic disks through a series of rings.

Ringers was played in an arena in which were suspended many moving metallic rings. The rings varied in size, shape, and movement pattern;<ref name="SWG">{{GalaxiesAED}}</ref> some moved in irregular arcs, others in a spiraling orbit.<ref name="Ringers">{{JournalCite|6|Ringers (short story)}}</ref> Standing on a line, the tossers took turns trying to throw the disks through multiple rings, called "making a ringer." To limit opportunities for cheating, all tossers shared the same equipment. Making a ringer required great skill and patience, and a skilled competitor knew how to wait for the rings to align for an advantageous shot. This made for a slow-paced game that Imperial [[Special Investigations squad|investigator]] [[Zeck Tambell]] compared to "watching [[Duracrete/Legends|duracrete]] dry." The excitement of watching ringers largely came from [[Gambling/Legends|gambling]] on the tournaments.<ref name="Ringers" /> The sport was popular on the planet [[Stassia]] during the era of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]].<ref name="SWG" />

